     <br>
I am an environmental scientist, a geologist. I cannot reiterate the entire case for my viewpoint here, but I believe that the Earth cannot support even its present population indefinitely. This is not the worst of it, though. There are almost three times as many people on Earth as there were when I was born. There may be twice as many again by the time I die. There is little evidence that population control measures are having any significant success, even when supported by the most draconian and repugnant coercion. <br>
    <br>
I don't believe that consumption in the industrialized countries can be significantly reduced even with the imposition of a totalitarian police state, something that many advocate but which is impossible in the face of the likely level of resistance. Even if it could be, there are still the material aspirations of Third World and traditional &quot;have not&quot; populations. As indicated in an <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showMessage?topicID=196.topic">earlier string</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, the conflict between these and various environmental measures is becoming more and more obvious. <br>
    <br>
What do we say to the African miner or the Brazilian secretary who represent the first generation of their families to have electricity, running water, and private automobiles? &quot;Sorry, folks, party's over, you got here too late.&quot;<br>
<br>
The real advocates of unrestrained growth are not in corporate high-rises and upscale suburbs, they are in the slums and rural villages of the Third World.<br>
    <br>
It would appear that economic and industrial growth, and the attendant destruction of the natural ecosystem, are inevitable; but there is another option. Industrial growth would not be such a hazard to the Earth if it were not taking place on the Earth. This notion is often laughed at. Indeed, if the current state of our space program were really the best we could do, the laughter would be justified: The current sytem could put my backyard garden into lunar orbit for, say, a couple of hundred billion dollars. A variety of people, from Carl Sagan to Gerard K. O'Neill to ourselves, have demonstrated that this is not the best we can do, and that growth need not be confined to the Earth. In fact, it will eventually be a matter of life and death that it not be. <br>
    <br>
ELF proposes a drastic and visionary solution. So do I, but my solution would allow the human race to expand for thousands of years, providing a chance for evolution to finish its work and close the gap between our nature and our capability.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A> at: 5/27/03 5:17:35 pm<br></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace>NuclearSpace Message Board</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5>Opposition Movements, Myths & Snake Oil</a> <font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.com">NuclearSpace Home Page</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.246c<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

